Document: 2D Transforms
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/2d_transforms.rst
Summary: This tutorial explains how to handle input events with correct coordinate systems in Godot's 2D transforms.

This is an overview of the 2D transforms going on for nodes from the moment they draw their content locally to the time they are drawn onto the screen. This overview discusses very low-level details of the engine. The goal of this tutorial is to teach a way for feeding input events to the Input with a position in the correct coordinate system. A more extensive description of all coordinate systems and 2d transforms is available in doc_2d_coordinate_systems.
---CHUNK---
Document: 2D Transforms
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/2d_transforms.rst
Summary: Explains how CanvasItem nodes use Canvas Layers with Transform2D for positioning and transformation

CanvasItem nodes (including Node2D and Control-based nodes) reside in Canvas Layers, each with a Transform2D that handles translation, rotation, and scaling. By default, nodes are drawn in Layer 0 of the built-in canvas. To place nodes in different layers, use a CanvasLayer node which allows assigning nodes to alternative canvas layers. The Transform2D of each canvas layer determines how its contents are positioned and transformed within the scene.
---CHUNK---
Document: 2D Transforms
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/2d_transforms.rst
Summary: Viewports have a Global Canvas transform that serves as the master transform for all Canvas Layers.

Viewports also have a Global Canvas transform (also a Transform2D). This is the master transform and affects all individual Canvas Layer transforms. Generally, this is primarily used in Godot's CanvasItem Editor.
---CHUNK---
Document: 2D Transforms
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/2d_transforms.rst
Summary: Explains the Stretch Transform in viewports for screen resizing and coordinate conversion.

Viewports have a Stretch Transform used when resizing or stretching the screen. This transform is used internally (as described in Multiple Resolutions) but can also be manually set on each viewport. Input events are multiplied by this transform, but lack the ones above. Note: The CanvasItem.make_input_local() function was added for convenience to convert InputEvent coordinates to local CanvasItem coordinates.
---CHUNK---
Document: 2D Transforms
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/2d_transforms.rst
Summary: Explains the role of the window transform in scaling and positioning content within a Window to maintain aspect ratios

The root viewport is a Window. In order to scale and position the Window's content as described in doc_multiple_resolutions, each Window contains a window transform. It is for example responsible for the black bars at the Window's sides so that the Viewport is displayed with a fixed aspect ratio.
---CHUNK---
